@page "/graph/expression-tree"
@using SymBlazor.Graphing
@inject NavigationManager Navigation

<div class="page-shell graph-page-shell">
    <section class="hero content-hero graph-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Sym / Graphing</p>
        <h1>Expression Tree</h1>
        <p class="hero-copy">
            This page shows how Sym parsed the input into a tree of operators, functions, constants, and symbols. It is
            a structural view rather than a numeric graph, but it is often the most direct way to understand what the
            symbolic engine is actually working with.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
            <a class="button-link primary" href="@GraphHomeHref">Graph Home</a>
            <a class="button-link secondary" href="/library/index.html">Library Home</a>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section grid-two">
        <article class="panel prose">
            <span class="mini-label">Reading The Tree</span>
            <h2>Structure Comes Before Evaluation</h2>
            <p>
                The expression tree shows how Sym grouped operators and operands before any graphing or numeric
                evaluation happened. That structural view is what later makes substitution, differentiation, rewriting,
                and matching possible.
            </p>
            <p>
                It is also the cleanest reminder that symbolic systems do not work on raw text. They work on explicit
                mathematical structure.
            </p>
        </article>
        <article class="panel prose">
            <span class="mini-label">Practical Tip</span>
            <h2>Useful For Debugging Input Shape</h2>
            <p>
                If a formula behaves differently than you expected, the tree is often the quickest way to spot how the
                parser actually associated powers, products, sums, and function arguments. It is a direct check on the
                symbolic structure Sym is using internally.
            </p>
            <p>
                That makes this page helpful not only for learning, but also for debugging expressions before they go
                into later symbolic workflows.
            </p>
        </article>
    </section>

    <section class="section graph-workbench graph-workbench-single">
        <article class="panel graph-controls">
            <span class="mini-label">Input</span>
            <h2>Expression</h2>

            <label class="graph-label">Formula
                <input class="graph-input" @bind="_expressionText" />
            </label>

            <button class="button-link primary graph-button" @onclick="RenderTree">Build Tree</button>

            <p class="graph-note">Example: <code>sin(x) + (x^2 / (1 + y))</code></p>
            @if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(_error))
            {
                <div class="graph-error">@_error</div>
            }
        </article>

        <article class="panel graph-output">
            <span class="mini-label">Structure</span>
            <h2>Parsed Tree</h2>

            @if (_rootNode is not null)
            {
                <div class="expression-tree-shell">
                    <ul class="expression-tree-root">
                        <ExpressionTreeNodeView Node="@_rootNode" />
                    </ul>
                </div>
            }
        </article>
    </section>

    <section class="section grid-two">
        <article class="panel prose">
            <span class="mini-label">What To Look For</span>
            <h2>Operators Become Internal Nodes</h2>
            <p>
                Functions, binary operators, and grouped subexpressions appear as higher nodes in the tree, while
                constants and symbols show up at the leaves. That shape is exactly what later rule systems inspect when
                they decide whether a simplification or transformation applies.
            </p>
        </article>
        <article class="panel prose">
            <span class="mini-label">Why It Matters</span>
            <h2>Tree Shape Affects Every Later Step</h2>
            <p>
                Once the parser commits to a structure, everything downstream depends on it. Matching, substitution,
                differentiation, and canonicalization all inherit the same tree, which is why seeing that structure
                directly can be so useful.
            </p>
        </article>
    </section>

    <div class="product-shell">
        <iframe class="product-frame" src="/ProductSection.html" title="ProductSection" loading="lazy"></iframe>
    </div>
    <footer class="site-footer">Copyright SymbolicComputation.com 2026. AI assisted.</footer>
</div>

@code {
    private string _expressionText = "sin(x) + (x^2 / (1 + y))";
    private GraphMath.ExpressionTreeNode? _rootNode;
    private string? _error;
    private string GraphHomeHref => $"{Navigation.BaseUri}graph";

    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        RenderTree();
    }

    private void RenderTree()
    {
        try
        {
            _rootNode = GraphMath.BuildExpressionTree(_expressionText);
            _error = null;
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            _error = ex.Message;
            _rootNode = null;
        }
    }
}
